## 3.2.1.3 Implied alpha

### Purpose

This subsection defines implied alpha, which is the alpha level implied by a given order size under the pre-trade cost model.

### Setup / formulation

Given an observed or intended order size $Q_T$, implied alpha is:

$$
\tilde{\alpha} = \Lambda_T Q_T.
$$

### Main result

Implied alpha lets the trader infer what alpha assumption would rationalize an order of size $Q_T$.

### Interpretation

If an order is too large relative to realized alpha, it may have been oversized. If it is too small relative to realized alpha, it may have left opportunity untraded.

Under the no-intraday-alpha OW benchmark:

$$
\text{realized alpha} \approx \tilde{\alpha},
$$

while target impact is approximately:

$$
I_t^* \approx \frac{1}{2}\tilde{\alpha}.
$$

Thus, implied alpha and realized alpha are compared to each other; optimal impact is not generally equal to alpha.

