## 3.2.1.4 The square-root law

### Purpose

This subsection explains how the pre-trade cost model changes for sizable orders when impact is globally concave.

### Setup / formulation

For large orders, linear impact may overstate or misrepresent the cost curve. The chapter refers to globally concave impact models such as the Alfonsi-Fruth-Schied model.

A generic globally concave impact form is:

$$
I_t = \operatorname{sign}(J_t)|J_t|^c,
\qquad 0<c<1.
$$

The square-root case corresponds to:

$$
c=\frac{1}{2}.
$$

### Main result

For sizable orders, impact grows sublinearly in size. A square-root law gives:

$$
I \propto \operatorname{sign}(Q)\sqrt{|Q|}.
$$

### Interpretation

Large orders still become more expensive as size increases, but the impact state does not grow linearly with order size. This changes order sizing and clean-up cost calculations.

