## 3.2.3.1 Quantifying deviation’s impact

### Purpose

This subsection shows how to measure the impact cost caused by deviations from the optimal schedule.

### Setup / formulation

Use the deviation state:

$$
\delta I_t = I_t(Q^r)-I_t(Q).
$$

The deviation evolves as:

$$
d\delta I_t
=
-\beta_t\delta I_t dt
+
\lambda_t d\delta Q_t.
$$

The expected P&L penalty is quadratic in $\delta I_t$.

### Main result

Impact-space deviation, not raw trade-space deviation, is the correct object to penalize.

### Interpretation

Two trade deviations can have very different costs if one creates persistent impact and the other quickly mean-reverts.

