## 3.3.2 An experiment to size orders correctly

### Purpose

This section shows how TCA can test whether orders were sized correctly.

### Setup / formulation

Assume no intraday trading alpha beyond the pre-trade signal. Then the pre-trade model implies:

$$
\tilde{\alpha} = \Lambda_T Q_T.
$$

The realized alpha should match implied alpha in expectation:

$$
\mathbb{E}[\text{realized alpha} \mid \tilde{\alpha}]
\approx
\tilde{\alpha}.
$$

The target impact should be approximately:

$$
I_t^* \approx \frac{1}{2}\tilde{\alpha}.
$$

### Main result

A TCA report can compare realized alpha and implied alpha to determine whether order sizes were too large, too small, or correctly calibrated.

### Interpretation

If realized alpha is lower than implied alpha, the portfolio team may be over-sizing orders. If realized alpha is higher, the portfolio may be under-trading opportunities.

